<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1296,499,528]" box="[151,1296,499,528]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,1296,499,528]" fontSize="12" level="1" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,1296,499,528]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName authority="Novis &amp; Braidwood &amp; Kilroy, 2012" authorityName="Novis &amp; Braidwood &amp; Kilroy" authorityYear="2012" box="[151,424,499,527]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthidiaceae" genus="Planothidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="victori" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,424,499,527]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Planothidium victori</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[432,534,499,528]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
P.M. Novis, J. Braidwood &amp; C. Kilroy (
<figureCitation box="[1075,1223,499,528]" captionStart="FIGURE 13–41" captionStartId="10.[151,244,1565,1586]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-333@10.[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 13–41. Planothidium spp. from the Styx River. Scales: Fig. 17, 5 µm (use for 13–20, 26–39); others 1 µm. Figs 13–25. Planothidium frequentissimum strain LCR-S:2:1:1, CHR618407. Figs 13–20, Cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 13–15, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure; Figs 16–18, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules). Figs 19, 20, variation seen in girdle view, with convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 21–25, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 21, raphid valve; Fig. 22, araphid valve with horseshoe visible; Fig. 23, internal view of araphid valve showing structure of horseshoe; Fig. 24, internal view of half of raphid valve; Fig. 25, araphid valve with depressed pseudoraphe. Figs 26–41. Planothidium victori strain LCR-S:18:1:1, CHR618408. Figs 26–39, cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 26–31, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure and curved valve margin especially in smaller valves; Figs 32–37, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules); Fig. 38, small araphid valve with horseshoe and hooked apex showing that the valve hook can occur at either end with respect to the horseshoe (compare with 30, 31); Fig. 39, girdle view showing convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 40, 41, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 40, araphid valve with horseshoe attachment visible; Fig. 41, oblique view of raphid valve." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5062010" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5062010/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Figs 26–41</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1237,1286,499,528]" captionStart="FIGURE 161" captionStartId="27.[151,246,1373,1394]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,351,1328]" captionTargetId="figure-325@27.[151,1436,346,1352]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 161. Bayesian phylogenies of Planothidium strains from the Styx River, for 18S rDNA (left) and rbcL (right). Support numbers above branches are Bayesian posterior probabilities / Maximum Parsimony bootstrap values. Scale bar = 0.1 subsitutions/ site. See text for substitution models and description of data sets." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5062038" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5062038/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">161</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,576,855]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">
Frustules elliptic-lanceolate in valve view, monoraphid, 14.0– 
<quantity box="[829,920,576,599]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.65" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="16.5">16.5 µm</quantity>
long, 5.0– 
<quantity box="[1040,1118,576,599]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="5.2">5.2 µm</quantity>
wide. Frustules rotationally asymmetric to a variable degree in valve view, from almost linear to slightly curved near one pole to incised near one pole to form a hook. Striae transverse to slightly radiate at central area to more strongly radiate at poles, 14–15(–16) in 
<quantity box="[229,304,672,695]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 µm</quantity>
, multiseriate. Araphid valve asymmetric at central area where striae are interrupted by a “hoofmark” structure (
<figureCitation box="[308,390,704,727]" captionStart="FIGURE 13–41" captionStartId="10.[151,244,1565,1586]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-333@10.[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 13–41. Planothidium spp. from the Styx River. Scales: Fig. 17, 5 µm (use for 13–20, 26–39); others 1 µm. Figs 13–25. Planothidium frequentissimum strain LCR-S:2:1:1, CHR618407. Figs 13–20, Cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 13–15, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure; Figs 16–18, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules). Figs 19, 20, variation seen in girdle view, with convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 21–25, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 21, raphid valve; Fig. 22, araphid valve with horseshoe visible; Fig. 23, internal view of araphid valve showing structure of horseshoe; Fig. 24, internal view of half of raphid valve; Fig. 25, araphid valve with depressed pseudoraphe. Figs 26–41. Planothidium victori strain LCR-S:18:1:1, CHR618408. Figs 26–39, cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 26–31, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure and curved valve margin especially in smaller valves; Figs 32–37, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules); Fig. 38, small araphid valve with horseshoe and hooked apex showing that the valve hook can occur at either end with respect to the horseshoe (compare with 30, 31); Fig. 39, girdle view showing convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 40, 41, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 40, araphid valve with horseshoe attachment visible; Fig. 41, oblique view of raphid valve." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5062010" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5062010/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
; 
<emphasis box="[403,462,704,727]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bukhtiyarova, L. &amp; Round, F. E." box="[470,788,704,727]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" pagination="1 - 30" refId="ref17473" refString="Bukhtiyarova, L. &amp; Round, F. E. (1996) Revision of the genus Achnanthes sensu lato. Psammothidium, a new genus based on A. marginulatum. Diatom Research 11: 1 - 30." type="journal article" year="1996">Round &amp; Bukhtiyarova 1996</bibRefCitation>
) appressed to inner valve surface. Position of hooked pole relative to hoofmark shows that hook can occur at either pole (but never both; 
<figureCitation box="[1078,1160,736,759]" captionStart="FIGURE 13–41" captionStartId="10.[151,244,1565,1586]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-333@10.[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 13–41. Planothidium spp. from the Styx River. Scales: Fig. 17, 5 µm (use for 13–20, 26–39); others 1 µm. Figs 13–25. Planothidium frequentissimum strain LCR-S:2:1:1, CHR618407. Figs 13–20, Cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 13–15, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure; Figs 16–18, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules). Figs 19, 20, variation seen in girdle view, with convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 21–25, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 21, raphid valve; Fig. 22, araphid valve with horseshoe visible; Fig. 23, internal view of araphid valve showing structure of horseshoe; Fig. 24, internal view of half of raphid valve; Fig. 25, araphid valve with depressed pseudoraphe. Figs 26–41. Planothidium victori strain LCR-S:18:1:1, CHR618408. Figs 26–39, cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 26–31, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure and curved valve margin especially in smaller valves; Figs 32–37, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules); Fig. 38, small araphid valve with horseshoe and hooked apex showing that the valve hook can occur at either end with respect to the horseshoe (compare with 30, 31); Fig. 39, girdle view showing convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 40, 41, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 40, araphid valve with horseshoe attachment visible; Fig. 41, oblique view of raphid valve." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5062010" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5062010/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Araphid valve slightly convex, raphid valve slightly concave; frustules thus curved in girdle view (
<figureCitation box="[1047,1129,768,791]" captionStart="FIGURE 13–41" captionStartId="10.[151,244,1565,1586]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetId="figure-333@10.[151,1436,351,1543]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 13–41. Planothidium spp. from the Styx River. Scales: Fig. 17, 5 µm (use for 13–20, 26–39); others 1 µm. Figs 13–25. Planothidium frequentissimum strain LCR-S:2:1:1, CHR618407. Figs 13–20, Cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 13–15, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure; Figs 16–18, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules). Figs 19, 20, variation seen in girdle view, with convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 21–25, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 21, raphid valve; Fig. 22, araphid valve with horseshoe visible; Fig. 23, internal view of araphid valve showing structure of horseshoe; Fig. 24, internal view of half of raphid valve; Fig. 25, araphid valve with depressed pseudoraphe. Figs 26–41. Planothidium victori strain LCR-S:18:1:1, CHR618408. Figs 26–39, cleaned frustules viewed by LM; Figs 26–31, araphid valve showing horseshoe structure and curved valve margin especially in smaller valves; Figs 32–37, raphid valve (vertical pairs are through-focus images of the same frustules); Fig. 38, small araphid valve with horseshoe and hooked apex showing that the valve hook can occur at either end with respect to the horseshoe (compare with 30, 31); Fig. 39, girdle view showing convex araphid valve and concave raphid valve. Figs 40, 41, SEM of cleaned frustules. Fig. 40, araphid valve with horseshoe attachment visible; Fig. 41, oblique view of raphid valve." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5062010" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5062010/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
), 
<quantity box="[1152,1278,768,791]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="4.05" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.6">3.6–4.5 µm</quantity>
wide. Raphe straight, with expanded proximal area and terminal fissures curved towards the secondary valve side; internally, central ends are weakly curved. Sternum linear.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
